To identify regions in the genome that are similar to each other, we decided to use the clustering method. Clustering allows to build groups of data based on their similarity. This is useful for various reasons. The first reason is that we can observe differences in the signal under the three conditions with the help of a heatmap, while these would look more similar without any clustering. Secondly, as the members of one group have similar characteristics, it will be easier to identify significant effects with appropriate analyses. For example, doing a GO analysis on the different clusters will allow to find what is most likely the function of these genes. As genes in the genomes perform a wide variety of functions, performing a GO analysis on clusters is more likely going to give positive results.

We decided to perform a separated clustering on GR and MR data to have the best clusters for each receptor. For each receptor, we collected the peaks and we used the input coverage of each condition as tracks to compute the signal around the peak regions. We firstly computed several clustering options (different number of clusters), and with the help of a plot showing the explained variance as a function of the number of clusters we determined the number of clusters we wanted to use with the “elbow method”, i.e. we chose the number of clusters after which further increasing would not lead to a large difference in terms of the explained variance. The number of clusters we chose in the end is six, but the choice remains subjective.

From the heatmaps, for both GR and MR, we can see differences across conditions. Without clusters we can already see that globally there is more signal in the FS30 condition and in the BLPM condition, compared to the BLAM control. However, with the help of clustering, we can actually see that the signal in some regions stays more similar across conditions, while in some clusters we can see more signal in the FS30 condition and/ or in the BLPM condition, and we can evence see differences between these conditions, while it seems there is more signal in the BLAM condition, probably suggesting that the functions of those regions are suppressed upon stress and/ or in the late afternoon, when the level of glucocorticoids is higher. Rattus norvegicus is a nocturnal animal (Cuesta et al., 2009) and as a nocturnal animal, it has higher glucocorticoid release late in the afternoon, just before its active phase starts (Dickmeis, 2009). Similarly, glucocorticoid release is known to be a reaction to stress (Whirledge & Cidlowski, 2010). GO analysis results will help to see whether the functions of the regions in those specific clusters are consistent with previous findings.
